SIMPLE: puerile
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Puerile
<hw>Pu"er*ile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>puerilis</ets>, fr. <ets>puer</ets> a child, a boy: cf. F.
<ets>pu⟦eacute⟧ril</ets>.]</ety> <def>Boyish; childish; trifling;
silly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The French have been notorious through generations for their
<qex>puerile</qex> affectation of Roman forms, models, and historic
precedents.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Youthful; boyish; juvenile; childish; trifling;
weak. See <er>Youthful</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puerilely</ent>⟦br⟧
